---
/** Hub: freelance floor rate. Worked example by freelanceRate(). */
import Base from '../../layouts/Base.astro';
import FreelanceRateCalculator from '../../components/calculators/FreelanceRateCalculator.tsx';
import { freelanceRate } from '../../lib/se-business';
import { formatMoney } from '../../lib/tax-engine';

const ex = freelanceRate(80000, 6000, 'CA', 'single', 6, 25, 40);
---

<Base
  title="Freelance rate calculator — the hourly rate you need"
  description="Work out the floor hourly rate to hit your target take-home as a freelancer, after self-employment tax, income tax, business expenses and unbilled hours."
>
  <section class="hero">
    <p class="hero-label">Freelance</p>
    <h1>Freelance rate calculator</h1>
    <p class="tagline">Your salary ÷ 2,080 is not your rate. Taxes, expenses and unbilled hours push it far higher.</p>
  </section>

  <p>
    New freelancers guess a rate by dividing a salary by 2,080 hours. That misses
    everything: self-employment tax, income tax, business expenses, time off, and the
    fact that only some hours are billable. This solves the other way — from the
    take-home you need back to the floor hourly rate that delivers it.
  </p>

  <FreelanceRateCalculator client:load />

  <h2>Worked example — {formatMoney(80000)} take-home in California</h2>
  <p>
    A California freelancer wants {formatMoney(80000)} in the bank, has {formatMoney(6000)}
    of expenses, bills 25 hours a week, and takes 6 weeks off:
  </p>
  <table class="data-table">
    <thead><tr><th>Figure</th><th>Amount</th></tr></thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr><td>Target take-home</td><td>{formatMoney(80000)}</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Gross revenue required</td><td>{formatMoney(ex.grossRevenue)}</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Billable hours a year</td><td>{formatMoney(ex.annualBillableHours)}</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Floor hourly rate</td><td>{formatMoney(ex.hourlyRate)}/hr</td></tr>
      <tr><td>A typical 40-hour project</td><td>{formatMoney(ex.projectRate)}</td></tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>
  <p>
    To keep {formatMoney(80000)}, this freelancer must bill {formatMoney(ex.hourlyRate)}
    an hour — because {formatMoney(ex.grossRevenue)} of revenue, spread over only
    {formatMoney(ex.annualBillableHours)} billable hours, is what survives taxes and
    expenses to leave {formatMoney(80000)}. A rate that "feels like" a good salary is
    usually far too low once you do this math.
  </p>

  <h2>Questions</h2>
  <div class="faq">
    <h3>Why is my floor rate so much higher than a salary wage?</h3>
    <p>
      Because a {formatMoney(80000)} salary hides a lot: the employer paid half your
      FICA, covered benefits, and paid you for 2,080 hours. Freelancing, you pay the
      full 15.3% self-employment tax, buy your own benefits, and bill perhaps 25 hours
      a week. All of that has to come out of your rate.
    </p>
  </div>
  <div class="faq">
    <h3>What are billable hours?</h3>
    <p>
      The hours you can actually charge for. Sales calls, admin, invoicing, marketing
      and learning are real work but unbillable, so most freelancers bill 20–30 of a
      40-hour week. Your rate has to cover the unbillable hours too, which is why
      lowering billable hours raises the floor rate.
    </p>
  </div>
  <div class="faq">
    <h3>Is the floor rate what I should charge?</h3>
    <p>
      No — it is the minimum to survive at your target. What you actually charge
      should be your market rate: what clients in your niche pay. If the market rate
      is above your floor, charge the market rate. If it is below, the niche can't
      support your income goal at those hours.
    </p>
  </div>
  <div class="faq">
    <h3>Does an S-corp change this?</h3>
    <p>
      It can, at higher incomes, by cutting self-employment tax on the distribution
      portion — which lowers the revenue you need and so the floor rate. See the
      <a href="/s-corp-tax-calculator/">S-corp calculator</a> for whether it pays off
      at your numbers.
    </p>
  </div>

  <h2>Related tools</h2>
  <ul class="link-columns">
    <li><a href="/1099-tax-calculator/">1099 tax calculator</a> — the tax on your freelance profit</li>
    <li><a href="/hourly-to-salary-calculator/">Hourly to salary calculator</a> — the reverse view</li>
    <li><a href="/self-employed-retirement-calculator/">Self-employed retirement</a></li>
  </ul>

  <p class="results-note">
    Estimate for the 2026 tax year. A floor, not a market rate. Not tax or business
    advice.
  </p>
</Base>
